        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Required sensitivity: The total amount of time of 3 hours is constrained by ALMA to have a good parallactic angle coverage for the polarization calibrator. The rms noise achieved in this total time is of 16 microJy/Beam or a 1% detection at 3-sigma for a dust emission peak of only 5 mJy/Beam. The peak of the dust emission is expected to be 145 mJy/beam at 1mm and at 0.18 arcsec, so we will be able to detect the dust polarization over the whole envelope, with a good S/N even for the faintest parts of it.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator setup: We will use the FULL polarization mode, needed to detect the dust polarization.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirement: We ask for an angular resolution of about 0.18 arcsec, which is required to well resolve the dust emission (see Fig.1) from the envelope scales proposed (1500 AU). What is more, this angular resolution will allow us to resolve the magnetic field towards the two embedded cm sources located at the center of G31 and separated 0.2". We note that the SMA does not have the sensitivity to carry out polarimetric observation at an angular resolution of &lt;0.5 arcsec. The much higher image fidelity and sensitivity of ALMA will allow us to detect the dust polarized emission. For the uv range that ALMA provides in the requested configuration G31 has a source size of about 2 arcsec, well within the inner 1/3 of the ALMA primary beam, as requested for polarization observations.

The dust continuum emission towards G31 is very compact, with a size of about 2 arcsec at 1 mm (Beltran et al. 2005; Girart et al. 2009; Cesaroni et al. 2011).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
