        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since G31 is a hot core, the lines are bright, typically a few 10 K, especially HC3N and CH3OH that were detected with the SMA at moderate angular resolution (&gt;0.5 arcsec: Girart al. 2009). At the required angular resolution, maps with high image fidelity and good sensitivity can be otained in a reasonable integration time only with ALMA. We request 1.3 hours of telescope time, which will provide a sensitivity of 1.4 K (2.45 mJy/beam) with 1 km/s velocity channel. Our SMA observations have shown that the lines have brightness temperatures typically &gt;30K (&gt;50 mJy). This will allow us to detect with a S/N&gt;20 the line emission and properly determine the rotation velocity (to properly study the velocity field a good S/N is absolutely needed).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Correlator setup: We will use the base bands configured to provide total bandwidths of 0.2 to 0.9 GHz with a spectral resolution of 0.3 to 0.7 km/s. We will smooth the spectra to a resolution of 1 km/s, sufficient for our purposes because the molecular lines in G31 are known to have a line FWHM of about 8 km/s. G31 is a hot core with a very rich chemistry so it is adequate to use large bandwidths at high spectral resolution to check for possible line blending. In addition, the large bandwidth used will allow us to observe as a byproduct other molecular species that could also be excellent tracers of the densest part of this massive core.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging requirement: We ask for an angular resolution of about 0.18 arcsec, which is required to resolve the molecular emission from the inner part of the envelope and to distinguish the mm emission associated with the two embedded free-free sources located at the center of G31 and separated by 0.2". 

The line emission towards G31 is very compact, with a size of 2 arcsec at 1 mm (Beltran et al. 2005; Cesaroni et al. 2011), which can be imaged without requesting ACA.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
